article.description: Candice Wiggins scored the go-ahead basket with 1:34 left, then grabbed a rebound on the other end in Stanford's 61-58 victory over Texas Tech on Sunday.
article.headline: Cardinal can't hold on to 17-point first-half lead
article.linkText: Wiggins, Stanford hold off late Texas Tech rally
article.story:
SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- After two lopsided wins last week, Stanford was due for a close game.

Candice Wiggins scored the go-ahead basket with 1:34 left before grabbing a key rebound on the other end as the Cardinal (No. 5 ESPN/USA Today, No. 7 AP) escaped with a 61-58 victory over Texas Tech (No. 11, No. 12) on Sunday.

T'Nae Thiel made two free throws with 2.2 seconds remaining to seal it for Stanford (5-0) after the lead changed 11 times in the final 10 minutes.

Brooke Smith, a sophomore transfer from Duke, scored 10 of her 22 points in the final 9:33, Kelley Suminski had 13 points and Wiggins added 11. Thiel finished with eight points and eight rebounds.

"Everybody does their part, and today it was my turn," Smith said. "I think we were a little tight, but as the game wore on that wore away and we started hitting shots when we needed to."

Erin Grant led the Lady Raiders (1-1) with 18 points, making all seven of her free throws and scoring all but four of her points after halftime. Chesley Dabbs added 12 points and six boards.

Grant missed a jumper with 1:09 remaining, but Texas Tech got the ball back with 35.4 seconds left following a 30-second clock violation by Stanford. The Lady Raiders couldn't get a shot off but got another possession with 12.8 seconds left after a scramble for a loose ball.

Alesha Robertson missed a 3-pointer in the waning seconds and Thiel came up with the loose ball.

"At halftime we just told ourselves to come out and play better," Grant said. "We fought all the way back and got the lead. Then we let down on defense a little bit and let them score some easy baskets."

Texas Tech started its comeback on Grant's two free throws with 15:17 left to pull within 32-30. Grant's 3-pointer at 12:02 gave the Lady Raiders their first lead, 37-35.

"We just finally came out relaxed," Texas Tech coach Marsha Sharp said. "We settled in, found shots we liked, and our transition game was a little better. When you're down, you just have to stay patient and upbeat. We played good defense the whole time."

Stanford had lost the two previous meetings with Texas Tech, including 55-46 last December in Lubbock. The Cardinal committed 13 turnovers but held a 39-33 rebounding advantage.

Stanford coach Tara VanDerveer is quickly finding out that her new players can perform in close games.

"We are doing new stuff and playing new people," the 19th-year coach said. "I was disappointed in our turnovers and with some of the decisions we made, but that's a great team and it's a good win for us."

Stanford jumped out to a 12-0 lead and led by as many as 17 in the first half before the Lady Raiders made their move after halftime with a 27-6 run.

Stanford played its final game at Santa Clara's Leavey Center, the Cardinal's temporary home until a $30 million facelift is completed at Maples Pavilion next month.

The Cardinal played without point guard Susan King Borchardt, sidelined with a stress reaction in her left foot. VanDerveer is hopeful to have Borchardt back in the lineup to face Pepperdine on Dec. 10 when Maples reopens.
